<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-567-393  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 567 393.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 12 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow: huge new taxes on imported computers unveiled.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industrySoviet UnionComputersGovernment RegulationImportTax.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOSCOW: HUGE NEW TAXES ON IMPORTED COMPUTERS UNVEILED MOSCOW, U.S.S.R., 1990OCT 12 (NB) -- The Soviet Union has announced new taxes on every computerimported by a non-state-owned enterprise since July 1st, 1990.andP;  The new rulesannounced Oct 5, state that computers imported after July 1st, 1990 will betaxed according to the following rule: import price in U.S.andP;  dollars shouldbe converted into rubles using the &quot;official&quot; exchange rate (currently .64rubles per $1) and then multiplied by 8 for computers, cars, audio equipment,by 8 -15 for VCRs, TVs, electronic games, and by 15 for tape cassettes.andO;Exempt from this rule are state-owned importers, re-exporters, companiesintending to sell equipment locally for hard currency, and joint ventures'registered assets.andM;A tax of more than 10,000 rubles for $2000 worth of computer systems, forwhich the market value now is approximately 45,000-50,000 rubles isconsidered very high.andM;These rules will probably be changed by January 1st, 1991 or once a RussianRepublic customs department is created, importers suggest.andM;U.S.S.R.andP;  Ministry of Finances and Customs authorities announced that theywill tax even already completed deals in which goods crossed the border inJuly, August and September &quot;according to Council of Ministers' decision&quot; asthey said.andM;According to a Kommersant Moscow weekly estimate, this new tax can hurt thegrowing publishing industry and greatly reduce the number of PCs imported inthe country by free economy structures.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19901011/Contact: customs information service phone +7 095975-4460)</TEXT></DOC>